02:52:03,200 --> 02:52:10,720
"Each night more mice disappeared… and the new cat seemed to
be getting fatter."

1520
02:52:10,720 --> 02:52:16,720
"Soon the mice were really scared. Finally the old mouse
called a meeting."

1521
02:52:16,760 --> 02:52:19,520
"We have to do something," he said.

1522
02:52:19,520 --> 02:52:26,560
"If we can't get rid of this cat she'll end up eating us
all. We need a plan."

1523
02:52:26,560 --> 02:52:39,160
"The problem," said the old mouse, "is that you can't hear the cat coming. She moves silently in the darkness. You
don't know she's there...until it's too late."

1524
02:52:39,160 --> 02:52:42,920
"That's it!" said the young mouse.

1525
02:52:42,920 --> 02:52:52,840
"We get a bell and tie it round the cat's neck. The bell will ring every time the cat moves and we'll know where she
is so she'll never catch us."

1526
02:52:52,880 --> 02:52:55,720
"The mice all looked at each other."

1527
02:52:55,720 --> 02:52:58,800
"Not bad," said someone."

1528
02:52:58,800 --> 02:53:03,440
"Actually, that's brilliant!" said someone else."

1529
02:53:03,440 --> 02:53:15,080
"The mice leapt into action. One group found a little bell that had fallen off the back of the farmhouse door and
another found some string which had been holding up a scarecrow's trousers."

1530
02:53:15,080 --> 02:53:17,280
"See," said the young mouse.

1531
02:53:17,280 --> 02:53:27,320
"We have everything we need for my brilliant plan. That cat
has eaten her last mouse. All our troubles are over."

1532
02:53:27,320 --> 02:53:40,480
"The mice all cheered and patted the young mice on the back. The young mouse had saved everyone from being eaten and
suddenly he was a hero...for about ten seconds."

1533
02:53:40,520 --> 02:53:45,560
"Just one question," said the old mouse.

1534
02:53:45,560 --> 02:53:49,280
"Who's going to tie the bell on the cat?"

1535
02:53:49,280 --> 02:54:01,360
"The mice all went silent then looked at the young mouse. The young mouse looked at the floor. He didn't want that
job. Nobody wanted that job."

1536
02:54:01,360 --> 02:54:04,840
"Oh dear," said the old mouse.

1537
02:54:04,840 --> 02:54:10,960
"It's easy to say something but often harder to actually do
it."

1538
02:54:10,960 --> 02:54:12,920
THE TOO FAT FOX

1539
02:54:12,920 --> 02:54:39,200
"A bitter wind blew the last leaves from the trees as Fox
made his way across the fields in search of food."

1540
02:54:39,200 --> 02:54:59,840
"The lake had been frozen for weeks and the livestock were tucked up safe and warm in the farmer's winter barns. Fox
couldn't remember when he had last eaten. His skinny ribs stuck through his patchy, moth-eaten coat, his teeth chattered and the hard frosty ground hurt his paws as he walked."

1541
02:54:59,880 --> 02:55:17,880
"Not a chicken, not a bird, not a puny little rabbit…not a scrap of food for a fox to eat…I shall surely die of cold
and hunger," he muttered miserably as he huddled up against a gnarled old tree trunk for shelter."

1542
02:55:17,880 --> 02:55:32,600
"Earlier that morning, not far from where our Fox was crouching, Mrs Tom Cobbler was busy fussing around her
husband and shooing him out of the farmhouse."

1543
02:55:32,600 --> 02:55:56,680
"Here's yer shopping list Mr Tom Cobbler - one nice, juicy leg of pork, 2 kilos of potatoes, half a bag of carrots, 2
onions and some big, firm cooking apples for our Sunday lunch. Now don't you go forgetting anything Mr Tom Cobbler. You're the most forgetful man I ever knew!" and she waved a dishcloth at him."

1544
02:55:56,680 --> 02:56:07,880
"Yars, Mrs Tom Cobbler…er I mean… no dear, I won't forget." And he stuffed the shopping list in his trouser pocket and
walked off to market."

1545
02:56:07,880 --> 02:56:17,320
"It was a long, cold walk to market and it was a long, hard walk back with his rucksack full of his wife's Sunday
shopping."

1546
02:56:17,320 --> 02:56:27,120
"Mr Tom Cobbler decided to sit down for a moment's rest beside a tree. (The very tree our Mr Fox was going to huddle
close too later on.)"

1547
02:56:27,120 --> 02:56:36,320
"After his rest and before he set off down the lane he looked about for a place to hide his shopping bag and saw a
hollow in the tree trunk."

1548
02:56:36,320 --> 02:56:49,800
"Ah, that'll do, he said. "That'll keep it safe from foxes – that hole's far too small for a plump ol" fox to climb
through." And off he tramped up the hill towards the farmyard."

1549
02:56:49,800 --> 02:57:15,760
"Well…what a nice surprise for our Mr Fox crouching beside that very same tree later that morning. His sly foxy nose
began to twitch…and he sniffed the cold wintry air…there was a whiff of FOOD nearby! And it seemed to be coming from the hollow of the very tree he sat against."

1550
02:57:15,760 --> 02:57:30,520
"And because he was so very starved and thin – our TOO THIN MR FOX was able to slip easily through into the hole. And
what did he find inside? That's right! All Mrs Tom Cobbler's Sunday dinner!"

1551
02:57:30,520 --> 02:57:37,840
"And what did he do with it? That's right! He gobbled it all
up, lickity-quick."

1552
02:57:37,840 --> 02:57:54,080
"And he felt very full indeed…SO full in fact that our TOO THIN FOX had become TOO FAT FOX in a matter of ten minutes
flat! Too fat in fact to fit back through the hole."

1553
02:57:54,160 --> 02:58:07,320
"So our Mr Fox had to wait and wait for days and days until his plump little tummy turned thin once more…and he could
climb back out through the hole of the tree again and off in search of food."

1554
02:58:07,320 --> 02:58:12,440
"Which just goes to show – that if you wait long enough –
the problem

1555
02:58:12,440 --> 02:58:14,240
might go away."

1556
02:58:14,240 --> 02:58:17,440
"And what happened to old Mr Tom Cobbler that day?"

1557
02:58:17,480 --> 02:58:27,240
"Well, Mrs Tom Cobbler wasn't happy at all that he'd lost the Sunday roast - so he had turnip soup and potato peel pie
instead!"

1558
02:58:27,240 --> 02:58:29,320
THE RAT AND THE ELEPHANT

1559
02:58:29,320 --> 02:58:51,960
"A Rat was walking through the city. He was a very proud Rat
who believed that he was the most frightening animal alive."

1560
02:58:51,960 --> 02:58:55,920
"Oh, yes!" said the Rat to himself.

1561
02:58:55,920 --> 02:58:57,880
"Everyone's scared of me."

1562
02:58:57,880 --> 02:59:02,680
"Scary Rat coming through. Out of my way."

1563
02:59:02,720 --> 02:59:08,800
"The Rat turned a corner and saw a crowd of people standing
by the side of the road."

1564
02:59:08,800 --> 02:59:10,520
"Brilliant," thought the rat.

1565
02:59:10,520 --> 02:59:13,000
"I do like a crowd."

1566
02:59:13,040 --> 02:59:27,720
"He jumped out into the middle of the road right in front of the crowd and waited for the first scream... but there
wasn't one. Everybody was staring up the road. Nobody even noticed the Rat."

1567
02:59:27,720 --> 02:59:30,160
"Look everybody," said the Rat.

1568
02:59:30,160 --> 02:59:33,520
"Over here. Rat. See."

1569
02:59:33,520 --> 02:59:39,960
"Nothing happened. The people were all too busy looking up
the road."

1570
02:59:40,000 --> 02:59:42,440
"This is ridiculous," said the Rat.

1571
02:59:42,440 --> 02:59:45,880
"Are you all blind? Can't you see me?"

1572
02:59:45,920 --> 02:59:50,920
"Then the Rat saw what the people were looking at."

1573
02:59:50,920 --> 02:59:59,760
"An elephant was coming down the road. Sitting on the
elephant's back and stroking a large white cat rode the
King."

1574
02:59:59,760 --> 03:00:02,000
"Wow," said a man.

1575
03:00:02,000 --> 03:00:06,600
"Just look at the size of that elephant!"

1576
03:00:06,600 --> 03:00:09,080
"Never mind the elephant," said the Rat.

1577
03:00:09,120 --> 03:00:12,160
"What about me. Look at me. I'm a scary rat."

1578
03:00:12,200 --> 03:00:18,080
"Yes look at its wonderful long trunk," said a woman."

1579
03:00:18,080 --> 03:00:22,000
"That's just its nose," said the Rat.

1580
03:00:22,000 --> 03:00:23,640
"I've got a nose."

1581
03:00:23,680 --> 03:00:27,200
"And its huge ears," said a little girl."

1582
03:00:27,200 --> 03:00:32,560
"I've got ears," said the Rat, jumping up and down."

1583
03:00:32,600 --> 03:00:38,280
"But nobody was listening. They were too busy admiring the
enormous elephant."

1584
03:00:38,280 --> 03:00:42,920
"That is the most wonderful creature in the whole world,"
they all said."

1585
03:00:42,920 --> 03:00:47,000
"No...no!" said the Rat.

1586
03:00:47,000 --> 03:01:10,200
"There's nothing wonderful about elephants. How many legs have they got? Four like me. How many eyes have they got?
Two like me. What colour are they? Grey like me. See, I'm exactly the same as an elephant except an elephant's really slow and boring and I'm truly the most fierce and terrifying creature in the world."

1587
03:01:10,200 --> 03:01:15,720
"But nobody noticed the Rat... ...apart from the King's
Cat."

1588
03:01:15,760 --> 03:01:23,240
"Look at me...look at me. I'm exactly like an elephant "cept
better.

1589
03:01:23,280 --> 03:01:24,680
Elephant's are rubbish.

1590
03:01:24,680 --> 03:01:26,960
I am the most fierce and..."

1591
03:01:26,960 --> 03:01:30,560
"The Rat didn't finish what he was saying because..."

1592
03:01:30,600 --> 03:01:37,560
"...in an instant the white cat had run down the elephant's
trunk and was staring the Rat in the face."

1593
03:01:37,560 --> 03:01:46,160
"Exactly like an elephant, eh?" said the Cat looking down at
the Rat."

1594
03:01:46,160 --> 03:01:55,080
"Well maybe not exactly," said the Rat looking nervously at
the cat's sharp claws.

1595
03:01:55,080 --> 03:02:03,720
"Obviously my nose isn't quite as long...my ears are a bit
smaller...and I haven't got a king riding on my back…"

1596
03:02:03,720 --> 03:02:10,840
"Suddenly the Cat's paw flashed out and pinned the Rat to
the ground. The Rat couldn't move."

1597
03:02:10,840 --> 03:02:15,640
"Think I could do this to an elephant?" said the Cat."

1598
03:02:15,640 --> 03:02:19,080
"Um...not sure," said the Rat."

1599
03:02:19,080 --> 03:02:25,920
"The Cat scooped up the Rat and held him up to her mouth."

1600
03:02:25,920 --> 03:02:30,880
"Think I could do this to an elephant?" said the Cat."

1601
03:02:30,880 --> 03:02:36,360
"No, maybe not," said the Rat shaking in fear."

1602
03:02:36,360 --> 03:02:43,160
"Think I could eat an elephant in two seconds flat?" asked
the Cat."

1603
03:02:43,160 --> 03:02:47,320
"Nope," whispered the Rat."

1604
03:02:47,360 --> 03:02:54,120
"Look what I've found," said the Cat to the people putting
the terrified Rat back down on the ground."

1605
03:02:54,120 --> 03:03:01,600
"The Rat was shaking and looked so small and scared that
people weren't at all frightened of him."

1606
03:03:01,600 --> 03:03:03,440
"What is it?" said a man."

1607
03:03:03,440 --> 03:03:07,440
"Sort of mouse I think," said his wife.

1608
03:03:07,440 --> 03:03:09,760
"Funny little mouse thing probably."

1609
03:03:09,760 --> 03:03:23,160
"As he slunk away the Rat heard the Cat say "A rat and an elephant may be the same colour but that doesn't make them
the same size.

1610
03:03:23,160 --> 03:03:24,720
You remember that...

1611
03:03:24,720 --> 03:03:26,480
Mr Rat.""

1612
03:03:26,480 --> 03:03:43,520
"And the Rat did remember that. For ever."

1613
03:03:43,520 --> 03:03:55,440
THE ANT AND THE DOVE

1614
03:03:55,440 --> 03:03:58,040
"It was another hot, dry day in the forest…"

1615
03:03:58,080 --> 03:04:04,960
"Ant had been wandering over crinkly, dry leaves for days in
search of a nice, cool drink…"

1616
03:04:05,000 --> 03:04:15,440
"All I need is a drop of rain falling from a leaf – or a tiny pool of dew on a flower petal – or even a muddy
puddle…" he thought.

1617
03:04:15,440 --> 03:04:21,920
But it was so hot all the dew and puddles in the forest had
dried up."

1618
03:04:21,960 --> 03:04:27,320
"I'm so thirsty, that I have no choice," Ant sighed at last.

1619
03:04:27,320 --> 03:04:31,440
"I shall have to go in search of the Roaring River."

1620
03:04:31,440 --> 03:04:43,360
"Ant had been warned about the Roaring River. "It roars and it swirls and if you go too close, it will sweep you away,"
a wise owl had told him."

1621
03:04:43,360 --> 03:04:53,680
"But Ant was desperate. "The river has more drops of water than all the rain clouds in the world," he thought. "It's my
only hope of staying alive.""

1622
03:04:53,720 --> 03:05:03,160
"So Ant headed off. He plodded on and on through the trees,
until finally, he heard rushing water ahead…"

1623
03:05:03,200 --> 03:05:17,600
"Before him lay the Roaring River – as vast as a sea, or so it seemed to tiny Ant. The fast flowing waters looked
frightening – but Ant was too thirsty to feel fear…"

1624
03:05:17,600 --> 03:05:24,280
"He clambered down the river bank and bent his weary head
into the water to drink it up."

1625
03:05:24,280 --> 03:05:32,520
"The cool, sparkling water was so refreshing that Ant didn't
hear a roaring wave coming towards him…"

1626
03:05:32,600 --> 03:05:46,000
"Suddenly, he was flat on his back - his little legs in the air, being swept away by the water! "Help!" he cried.
"Someone save me, please!""

1627
03:05:46,040 --> 03:05:56,280
"All of a sudden, a green leaf dropped onto the water by his side with a plop. "Quick, climb on!" cried a gentle cooing
voice."

1628
03:05:56,320 --> 03:06:04,640
"Ant didn't have time to see who the voice belonged to. He just did what it told him…then he opened his eyes and looked
up."

1629
03:06:04,640 --> 03:06:09,840
"Perching on the branch of a tree above was a pure white
Dove."

1630
03:06:09,880 --> 03:06:18,280
"Stay calm, little Ant - and wait for the gentle breeze to
blow the leaf to the river bank," she cooed."

1631
03:06:18,280 --> 03:06:34,240
"Sure enough, the leaf carried Ant to safety. He looked up – but the Dove had disappeared. "I can't leave without
thanking her," he thought. "So I shall wait until she returns.""

1632
03:06:34,240 --> 03:06:44,760
"Ant waited and waited. Then, just as he was about to fall asleep, he heard strange noises. They were coming closer and
closer…"

1633
03:06:44,760 --> 03:07:08,200
"Two men emerged from the forest and stopped under the Dove's tree. One was carrying a bucket – the other a large,
golden cage. "This is the tree – the home of the most beautiful dove in the land," said the man with the cage. "I hope that glue in your bucket is sticky enough…""

1634
03:07:08,200 --> 03:07:14,280
"Indeed it is," said the second as he covered the branch
with a thick, green paste.

1635
03:07:14,280 --> 03:07:23,120
"When the Dove lands, its feet will stick to the branch – then we can put it in the cage and take it to the King. All
we have to do is hide and wait…"

1636
03:07:23,120 --> 03:07:35,760
"Ant was horrified. "I can't let this happen!" he thought. "But what can a tiny creature like me do against two such
giants of men?""

1637
03:07:35,800 --> 03:07:51,240
"Ant looked up as he heard the flapping of wings. The Dove had returned and was about to land on the sticky branch…!
"If I'm going to act, I must use the only weapon I have…" thought Ant. "And I must do it RIGHT NOW!""

1638
03:07:51,240 --> 03:07:58,440
"So he jumped onto the men's feet – and bit as hard as he
could…time and time again…"

1639
03:07:58,520 --> 03:08:04,000
"Yow!!!" they cried out in pain and took to their heels
through the forest."

1640
03:08:04,000 --> 03:08:11,800
"Thank you for saving me from a life in a cage," cooed the
Dove to Ant."

1641
03:08:11,800 --> 03:08:18,560
"And thank you for saving me from the giant wave," replied
Ant."

1642
03:08:18,560 --> 03:08:21,600
THE BOY WHO CRIED WOLF

1643
03:08:21,600 --> 03:08:25,440
"A young boy got a job with a shepherd."

1644
03:08:25,440 --> 03:08:41,400
"Just keep your eyes open and look out for wolves" said the
shepherd.

1645
03:08:41,400 --> 03:08:49,000
"Wolves always try to eat my sheep. If you see one, ring
this bell and shout out "Wolf..!

1646
03:08:49,000 --> 03:08:51,000
Wolf..!"

1647
03:08:51,000 --> 03:08:53,640
Then we'll come running with our guns.

1648
03:08:53,640 --> 03:08:56,000
Can you do that, boy?"

1649
03:08:56,040 --> 03:08:59,280
"Don't you worry Mr Shepherd," said the boy.

1650
03:08:59,280 --> 03:09:01,160
"Your sheep are safe with me.""

1651
03:09:01,160 --> 03:09:06,000
"The boy took the sheep up into the hills and sat down with
his bell."

1652
03:09:06,040 --> 03:09:08,400
"Don't worry sheep," he said.

1653
03:09:08,400 --> 03:09:13,360
"I'm here now. I'm in charge. You'll be safe with me."

1654
03:09:13,360 --> 03:09:23,440
"All morning the boy sat in the grass looking for wolves. "I
expect they're hiding," he said to the sheep."

1655
03:09:23,440 --> 03:09:35,080
"That night the boy took the sheep back to the village. The shepherd counted his sheep and was very pleased. "Well
done," he said. "All safe.

1656
03:09:35,080 --> 03:09:37,480
Same again tomorrow?""

1657
03:09:37,520 --> 03:09:40,600
"Yes sir!" said the boy."

1658
03:09:40,600 --> 03:09:56,040
"The next day was exactly the same as the first day. The boy took the sheep to the hills and sat down with his bell
looking for wolves."

1659
03:09:56,040 --> 03:09:57,840
"There weren't any."

1660
03:09:57,840 --> 03:10:13,560
"The boy noticed that the day felt very long. There was no-one to talk to...except sheep...and the sheep never
talked back...they just ate grass...all day..."

1661
03:10:13,560 --> 03:10:24,720
"By the fifth day the boy was very bored with his job. He
looked up at the mountains. Not a wolf in sight."

1662
03:10:24,720 --> 03:10:30,960
"He looked down at the bell and he thought: "Maybe I could
just pretend there's a wolf.""

1663
03:10:30,960 --> 03:10:42,960
"So he picked up his bell... ...and rang it, shouting "Wolf...wolf... ...hurry...come quickly...there's a big old
wolf coming!""

1664
03:10:43,000 --> 03:10:53,280
"Soon he could hear the sound of men running up the hill.
"Where is it?" said the shepherd. "Gone," said the boy."

1665
03:10:53,280 --> 03:10:57,480
"He just ran off." "Well done boy," said the shepherd.

1666
03:10:57,480 --> 03:11:07,840
"You saved my sheep." The other men all patted the boy on the head and said how brave he'd been and what a good job
he'd done.

1667
03:11:07,840 --> 03:11:15,920
The boy felt so proud and pleased with himself that he
almost forgot that he'd made the whole thing up."

1668
03:11:15,920 --> 03:11:31,040
"A few days later he was bored again. "The only good day I had in this job was when I pretended there was a wolf," he
told the sheep. "And I rang my bell and all the men came and told me what a good job I'd done.

1669
03:11:31,080 --> 03:11:32,480
It was brilliant.""

1670
03:11:32,520 --> 03:11:37,880
"He looked at his bell. And that's when he decided to do it
again."

1671
03:11:37,880 --> 03:11:49,480
"He rang, he shouted and again the men came running. "Where
is it?" said the shepherd. "Gone," said the boy. "Ran away."

1672
03:11:49,480 --> 03:11:54,280
This time the men didn't say "well done" and pat him on the
head.

1673
03:11:54,320 --> 03:11:57,800
This time they looked at the boy like they didn't believe
him.

1674
03:11:57,800 --> 03:11:59,800
"There was a wolf, honest," he said.

1675
03:11:59,800 --> 03:12:05,400
The men just walked back to the village without speaking."

1676
03:12:05,400 --> 03:12:13,800
"Now the boy felt really sorry for himself. "They know I
rang my bell when there was no wolf.""

1677
03:12:13,800 --> 03:12:24,680
"Then out of the corner of his eye he saw a movement - a big
grey thing was coming down the hillside heading straight for the sheep."

1678
03:12:24,720 --> 03:12:31,960
"The boy rang his bell and he shouted. "Wolf...wolf...come
quickly... ...there's a wolf!""

1679
03:12:31,960 --> 03:12:37,080
"Down in the village the men heard the bell ring and just
carried on working."

1680
03:12:37,080 --> 03:12:40,040
"Little fool," said the Shepherd.

1681
03:12:40,040 --> 03:12:43,600
"Does he really think we'll fall for that again?"

1682
03:12:43,600 --> 03:12:54,320
"The boy kept ringing his bell. There were tears in his eyes as he watched the wolf make a meal of one of the shepherd's
fattest sheep."

1683
03:12:54,360 --> 03:13:01,920
"I rang my bell but nobody came," the boy told the shepherd
that evening."

1684
03:13:01,920 --> 03:13:15,880
"The shepherd nodded "Nobody believes a liar...even when
he's speaking the truth."

